Study Information and Statement of informed Consent

1. Aim of the study

The purpose of this study is to investigate visual attention and its improvement through learning.

2. Procedure and content of the study

For this purpose, you will be asked to perform a simple task in which you classify clouds of moving dots.
Please only participate from a computer (no mobiles, no tablets) and if your screen is at least 13-inch diagonal.

3. What will happen to the data collected?

This study is a research project of the Max Planck Institute (MPI) for Human Development in cooperation with the University of Oxford.
The data collected will be used for research purposes only. The study data will be stored under an individual code number.
After payment, the key linking your Prolific ID to the individual code number will be deleted.
This means that it will become impossible to link the study data to you.

The study data (but not Prolific ID) may be shared with cooperation partners for collaborative analysis.
The study data may also be made publicly accessible via research data bases or scientific publications (typically via the Internet).
This makes it possible for other researchers to check or replicate the results and enhances the quality of scientific research.
The study data may also be used for new research questions going beyond the purposes of this particular study.
Study data are only transferred or made publicly accessible without Prolific IDs or any data in which persons are identifiable.

Press any key to continue to the next page.

subject: 1wqlvu38w6f5kun
stimulus:
4. Participation is voluntary

Participation in this study is voluntary. You may withdraw from the study at any time.
You may also withdraw your consent to data processing and usage at any time before payment.
To do so, please contact neuroexperiments@mpib-berlin.mpg.de.
Please note that data collected from you can no longer be associated with you, once your Prolific ID is deleted from the study data after payment.

5. Consent

The study will on average last about 20 minutes.
You will be paid 3£ for completing the experiment.
Please understand that we can only pay the compensation, if you finish.
Before being admitted to the task, you will have to pass three questions ensuring your understanding of the instructions and the English language.
We will ask you to do the task using full screen mode.
If you exit the full screen, this will be considered as quitting the experiment and we cannot pay you for that respective part.
If you don't consent to the conditions outlined on the last two pages, please exit the full screen now to abort the experiment.
Otherwise, press any key to continue to the consent page.

stimulus:
Dear participant,

Thank you very much for participating in our experiment!

In this task, you will see a cloud of coloured, moving dots on every trial.

Your task is to learn how to correctly classify the moving dots using two response keys.

The two response keys are y and m.

If you answered correctly, you will see a happy smiley. If your answer was incorrect, you will see a sad smiley.

Please try to answer while the dot cloud is displayed on the screen. It will be displayed for around 2 seconds.

Before starting the experiment, we will check whether you are a human, comprehend English and your understanding of the instructions with three questions.
This is a step we must take to protect the data quality.
Some questions are slightly tricky and require you to pay very close attention to all texts and to answer accordingly.
You must answer correctly to be able to take part in the experiment.
Otherwise you will be returned to Prolific and we cannot reimburse you.
Press any key to continue.

Information about the completed experiment

Thank you again for your participation in our experiment!

This study is a collaborative project from researchers of the Max Planck Institute for Human Development and the University of Oxford.
We investigate how performance on tasks, which are demanding on the visual attention, changes with practice.
Here, we are interested in how learning from feedback (instead of clear instructions) influences this change in performance.

If you have any further questions, please ask the responsible study experimenter.
